comments.body: Attempting to generate the pyramidal tiff now. This might be our biggest scroll - we'll see how it goes.

For now I generated the pyramidal manually. The final fix will be #3940. The command to do this is the following:

```ruby
resource_id = "4eae2e8a-5fd5-4792-bdea-8e2085465687"
change_set_persister = ::ChangeSetPersister.new(metadata_adapter: Valkyrie::MetadataAdapter.find(:indexing_persister), storage_adapter: Valkyrie::StorageAdapter.find(:pyramidal_derivatives))
VIPSDerivativeService.new(id: resource_id, storage_adapter: storage_adapter).create_derivatives
resource = change_set_persister.query_service.find_by(id: resource_id)
resource.processing_status = "processed"
change_set_persister.metadata_adapter.persister.save(resource: resource)
```

figgy.title: METS Ingest doesn't work for any(!?) PUDL collections

comments.body: IngestMETSJob is written to process a combined METS/MODS document that was generated by @jpstroop. We used to pull them off a google drive - I don't have them on hand, maybe @escowles does?
Doesn't show up here https://drive.google.com/drive/u/1/search?q=IsPartOf%20parent:1vM0mkt62UeRICyc45SlRnt9LgHxMnK-j
I'm assuming the short answer is to write some new code to handle the actual METS/MODS we have.

Or update the METS files to have the expected `IsPartOf` div? The files we ingested most of the PUDL content from had StructMaps that started like this:

```
<mets:structMap TYPE="RelatedObjects">
  <mets:div DMDID="q6wwb r7db1" ID="e4lns" LABEL="Default">
    <mets:div CONTENTIDS="pudl0001" TYPE="IsPartOf"/>
```

Also, I do have METS files with `IsPartOf` divs for most of PUDL, but I strongly suspect these are the collections that have already been ingested:

pudl0001, pudl0002, pudl0003, pudl0004, pudl0006, pudl0007, pudl0008, pudl0009, pudl0011, pudl0013, pudl0014, pudl0016, pudl0017, pudl0021, pudl0022, pudl0023, pudl0024, pudl0027, pudl0028, pudl0032, pudl0036, pudl0038, pudl0044, pudl0045, pudl0046, pudl0053, pudl0058, pudl0059, pudl0063, pudl0064, pudl0067, pudl0069, pudl0070, pudl0071, pudl0072, pudl0073, pudl0074, pudl0075, pudl0076, pudl0077, pudl0079, pudl0081, pudl0085, pudl0087, pudl0090, pudl0091, pudl0094, pudl0100, pudl0102, pudl0104, pudl0105, pudl0106, pudl0107, pudl0112, pudl0114, pudl0115, pudl0116, pudl0117, pudl0118, pudl0120, pudl0122, pudl0123, pudl0124, pudl0125, pudl0126, pudl0127, pudl0129, pudl0132, pudl0134, pudl0135, pudl0137, pudl0139

IngestMETSJob was created quite some time ago to ingest some hybrid METS/MODS @jpstroop created for (some) PUDL collections.  Based on discussion with @hackmastera and @tpendragon , I'll modify ingest_ephemera_mods to handle the GNIB MODS.

I don't think I ever 'compiled' pudl0066 (I really hope I can forget these numbers someday).
The METS that are used to ingest into Figgy have just a slightly different flavor (don't ask me what now) from the PUDL MODS, and there's some ancient code on a branch of PUDL that should be able to make the METS that you need: 

https://github.com/pulibrary/pudl_mets_compiler/tree/plum_migration

I can fire up my old dev machine in the next few days and see if it just works; not sure why it would be different from any other collection.
No worries, @jpstroop.  I met with @tpendragon and @hackmastera this afternoon, and I've now got it well in hand!

pomegranate.title: Suggest a correction form

comments.body: This seems like a different issue from #285. That one is a general feedback form as in the header on the catalog; this one is specific to a given record. What email address should this one submit to @kelea99 ?

@hackmastera it depends on the item and I would really like to hear your thoughts. I see  a couple of ways this can go--one is a bit of a pain, but more direct. the other seems like it would be programmatically easier (but I do not know)?
1. (Easier?): the correction suggestion goes to the exhibition owner(s).
2. The Correction Suggestion, depending on what the item/correction is, would be triaged:

**The metadata is incorrect in the DPUL/Figgy/Online Catalog record:**

- Any corrections requests for MARC/catalog records may be sent to: catalogn@princeton.edu

- Any corrections requests for EAD/Finding Aids: click on “suggest a correction” within the finding aid component itself or wherever that form is sent to ( would Kevin know this?)

- Any corrections requests for ephemeral items would go to the Selector who works with the ephemeral collection (examples include Gabrielle/Fernando for LAE, Thomas/Anna for Soviet, Ellen for SAE, etc.)

**If an item is described in an exhibition in DPUL incorrectly (in a curators note, or text within and exhibition, for example)**
- Contact Kim Leaman (kleaman@princeton.edu / Slack: Kelea) and/or the exhibition curator listed in the left hand column on the “About” pages within the exhibit.

**If the wrong metadata is associated with an item in Figgy and/or DPUL.** 
- Contact Kim Leaman (kleaman@princeton.edu / Slack: Kelea), and provide a link to the item in figgy/DPUL.

**If the images are oriented incorrectly in the viewer, pages are askew and/or missing in Figgy/DPUL.**
- Contact Kim Leaman (kleaman@princeton.edu / Slack: Kelea) or Roel Munoz (rmunoz@princeton.edu / Slack: Roel) and provide a link to the figgy/online catalog/DPUL URL, along with a description as to what is wrong with the images.

@kelea99 Either way works and it seems like a discussion to have with the exhibition owners. Option 1 we would do by pulling the email addresses from the exhibit record. Option 2 we would do by sending them all to a single / central email address (probably a metadata-oriented libguides email address?); and then the person monitoring that address would follow the workflow you lay out. We would just need to know what the email address is to send to.

@hackmastera I like the idea of option two, just to ensure the request gets through to the right people. OK, so we would need to have an said metadata-oriented libguides email address set up and go from there. I am happy to monitor that address as the primary point person, but it would be a good idea to have more folks than just me on that email/listserv (whatever it may be called in libguides).  @kevinreiss Im assuming you are the person to talk to regarding setting an email like this up?
Sorry I said libguides but I meant libanswers.

[Orangelight:alma_qa] alma_qa playbook will not add alma keys on the alma_qa1 box

comments.body: @christinach what are the keys and where can I find the desired values?
You can find them in the last pass in the Shared ITIMS
@hackmastera ^

So it looks like these are:

- ALMA_ACQ_READ_WRITE
- ALMA_BIB_READ_WRITE
- ALMA_BIBS_READ_ONLY
- ALMA_CONFIG_READ_ONLY
- ALMA_USERS_READ_ONLY
The `orangelight` role depends on the `blacklight-app` role which depends on `rails-app` which runs the task that sets up the env. Everything looks set up correctly to me. I'm going to run it.

The problem is that it's pulling from `roles/pulibrary.orangelight/vars/main.yml`. This file has a really high precedence and can't be overridden by playbook or group_vars. `defaults/main.yml` is the place to put defaults for a role, unless we never expect it to change from playbook to playbook (an example from @kayiwa in slack was "upstream repo keys"). Otherwise we should keep settings in group_vars files.
